Which Events are the Most Impactful?

Project Description

This analysis is to determine which natural events are the most impactful to humans. Impact is measured by injuries and fatalities to humans, as well as cost of damages incurred. Data is sourced from the National Weather Service, and was extracted from the Coursera Reproducible Research Peer Assessment 2 assignment page. Analysis was conducted on MAC OSX 10.11.6, with R version 3.3.0 using RStudio version 0.99.902

First, load in the R packages required for analysis.

library(ggplot2)
library(plyr)
library(dplyr)
library(R.utils)

Data Processing

Check to see if the StormData.csv.bz2 file, which is taken from the Coursera page, exists in the working directory. If it does, skip the download. If it does not, download the file from the site.

if (!file.exists("StormData.csv.bz2")) {
  tryCatch({
    download.file("https://d396qusza40orc.cloudfront.net/repdata%2Fdata%2FStormData.csv.bz2", "StormData.csv.bz2")
    print("File did not exist, but was successfully downloaded from the URL.")
  },
  error = function(cond) {
    print(
      "File did not exist, but there was an error in downloading the file from the provided URL."
    )
  })
} else {
  print("File StormData.csv.bz2 already exists")
}

Then, do a row count of events by year and see if there’s any distinguishable period of time where the number of events increases. This can be used as a way to determine when the data becomes a bit cleaner.

storm.data$year = as.numeric(format(as.Date(storm.data$BGN_DATE, format="%m/%d/%Y %H:%M:%S"), "%Y"))
storm.data.byyear <- aggregate(LENGTH ~ year, data = storm.data, FUN = function(x){NROW(x)})
colnames(storm.data.byyear) <- c('Year', 'NumberOfEvents')

storm.data.byyear.sorted = storm.data.byyear[order(storm.data.byyear$Year,decreasing = TRUE),]

storm.data.ready <- subset(storm.data, year >= 1994)

Now, using lookups in the also provided documents, remap the property damage exponent columns to be useful… Empty = 10^0, H = 10^2, K=10^3, M=10^6, B=10^9. Take PROPDMG column * exp(PROP_DMNG_EXP_NUM) column to create column DamageToProperty. To create column DamageToCrop, Rinse/Wash/Repeat with CROPDMNG and CROPDMGEXP.

storm.data.ready$PROP_DMG_EXP_NUM = as.character(storm.data.ready$PROPDMGEXP)

storm.data.ready$PROP_DMG_EXP_NUM[toupper(storm.data.ready$PROPDMGEXP) == ''] = "0"
storm.data.ready$PROP_DMG_EXP_NUM[toupper(storm.data.ready$PROPDMGEXP) == 'H'] = "2"
storm.data.ready$PROP_DMG_EXP_NUM[toupper(storm.data.ready$PROPDMGEXP) == 'K'] = "3"
storm.data.ready$PROP_DMG_EXP_NUM[toupper(storm.data.ready$PROPDMGEXP) == 'M'] = "6"
storm.data.ready$PROP_DMG_EXP_NUM[toupper(storm.data.ready$PROPDMGEXP) == 'B'] = "9"

storm.data.ready$PROP_DMG_EXP_NUM = as.numeric(storm.data.ready$PROPDMGEXP)
storm.data.ready$PROP_DMG_EXP_NUM[is.na(storm.data.ready$PROPDMGEXP)] = 0

storm.data.ready$DamageToProperty = storm.data.ready$PROPDMG * 10^storm.data.ready$PROP_DMG_EXP_NUM
storm.data.ready$CROP_DMG_EXP_NUM = as.character(storm.data.ready$CROPDMGEXP)
storm.data.ready$CROP_DMG_EXP_NUM[is.na(storm.data.ready$PROPDMGEXP)] = 0

storm.data.ready$CROP_DMG_EXP_NUM[toupper(storm.data.ready$CROPDMGEXP) == ''] = "0"
storm.data.ready$CROP_DMG_EXP_NUM[toupper(storm.data.ready$CROPDMGEXP) == 'H'] = "2"
storm.data.ready$CROP_DMG_EXP_NUM[toupper(storm.data.ready$CROPDMGEXP) == 'K'] = "3"
storm.data.ready$CROP_DMG_EXP_NUM[toupper(storm.data.ready$CROPDMGEXP) == 'M'] = "6"
storm.data.ready$CROP_DMG_EXP_NUM[toupper(storm.data.ready$CROPDMGEXP) == 'B'] = "9"

storm.data.ready$CROP_DMG_EXP_NUM = as.numeric(storm.data.ready$CROPDMGEXP)

Because there are so many event types, look only at the top 100 most impactful. Define impact as Total Damage. S the data by TotalDamage, and keep only the top 100. Do the same for Property and Crop, as well. Then, panel plot the three for comparison.

Before building the column and display the plots, add function multiplot, which is from an R cookbook. (Linked here: http://www.cookbook-r.com/Graphs/Multiple_graphs_on_one_page_(ggplot2)/)
multiplot <- function(..., plotlist=NULL, file, cols=1, layout=NULL) {
  require(grid)
  
  # Make a list from the ... arguments and plotlist
  plots <- c(list(...), plotlist)
  
  numPlots = length(plots)
  
  # If layout is NULL, then use 'cols' to determine layout
  if (is.null(layout)) {
    # Make the panel
    # ncol: Number of columns of plots
    # nrow: Number of rows needed, calculated from # of cols
    layout <- matrix(seq(1, cols * ceiling(numPlots/cols)),
                     ncol = cols, nrow = ceiling(numPlots/cols))
  }
  
  if (numPlots==1) {
    print(plots[[1]])
    
  } else {
    # Set up the page
    grid.newpage()
    pushViewport(viewport(layout = grid.layout(nrow(layout), ncol(layout))))
    
    # Make each plot, in the correct location
    for (i in 1:numPlots) {
      # Get the i,j matrix positions of the regions that contain this subplot
      matchidx <- as.data.frame(which(layout == i, arr.ind = TRUE))
      
      print(plots[[i]], vp = viewport(layout.pos.row = matchidx$row,
                                      layout.pos.col = matchidx$col))
    }
  }
}
storm.data.ready$TotalDamages = storm.data.ready$DamageToProperty + storm.data.ready$DamageToCrop
sorted.by.TotalDamage = storm.data.ready[order(storm.data.ready$TotalDamages,decreasing = TRUE),]
sorted.by.PropDamage = storm.data.ready[order(storm.data.ready$DamageToProperty,decreasing = TRUE),]
sorted.by.CropDamage = storm.data.ready[order(storm.data.ready$DamageToCrop,decreasing = TRUE),]
Top.100.TotalDamage <- head(sorted.by.TotalDamage,100)[,c('EVTYPE','TotalDamages')]
Top.100.PropDamage <- head(sorted.by.PropDamage,100)[,c('EVTYPE','DamageToProperty')]
Top.100.CropDamage <- head(sorted.by.CropDamage,100)[,c('EVTYPE','DamageToCrop')]

TotalDamage <- ggplot(data=Top.100.TotalDamage, aes(x=EVTYPE, y=TotalDamages)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity") +
  labs(x="Event Type", y="Total Damage") +
  ggtitle("Total Damage Caused by Event Type") +
  theme(axis.text=element_text(size=6),axis.title=element_text(size=8),axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

PropDamage <- ggplot(data=Top.100.PropDamage, aes(x=EVTYPE, y=DamageToProperty)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity") +
  labs(x="Event Type", y="Damage to Property") +
  ggtitle("Property Damage Caused by Event Type") +
  theme(axis.text=element_text(size=6),axis.title=element_text(size=8),axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

CropDamage <- ggplot(data=Top.100.CropDamage, aes(x=EVTYPE, y=DamageToCrop)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity") +
  labs(x="Event Type", y="Damage to Crops") +
  ggtitle("Crop Damage Caused by Event Type") +
  theme(axis.text=element_text(size=6),axis.title=element_text(size=8),axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

multiplot(TotalDamage,PropDamage,CropDamage)

Another consideration for impact is effect on people. Repeat the above with data related to impact to humans. Injury counts and fatality counts are available, so aggregate and create TotalPeople. Plot the INJURIES, FATALITIES, and TotalPeople Impact by Event type.

storm.data.ready$TotalPeople = storm.data.ready$INJURIES + storm.data.ready$FATALITIES
sorted.by.impacted.people = storm.data.ready[order(storm.data.ready$TotalPeople,decreasing = TRUE),]
sorted.by.injury = storm.data.ready[order(storm.data.ready$INJURIES,decreasing = TRUE),]
sorted.by.fatality = storm.data.ready[order(storm.data.ready$FATALITIES,decreasing = TRUE),]
Top.100.impacted.people <- head(sorted.by.impacted.people,100)[,c('EVTYPE','TotalPeople')]
Top.100.injury <- head(sorted.by.impacted.people,100)[,c('EVTYPE','INJURIES')]
Top.100.fatality <- head(sorted.by.impacted.people,100)[,c('EVTYPE','FATALITIES')]

TotalPeople <- ggplot(data=Top.100.impacted.people, aes(x=EVTYPE, y=TotalPeople)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity") +
  labs(x="Event Type", y="Total People Impacted") +
  ggtitle("Total Injuries/Death Caused by Event Type") +
  theme(axis.text=element_text(size=6),axis.title=element_text(size=8),axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

Injury <- ggplot(data=Top.100.injury, aes(x=EVTYPE, y=INJURIES)) +

  ggtitle("People injured Caused by Event Type") +

  labs(x="Event Type", y="People Killed") +
  ggtitle("Fatalities Caused by Event Type") +
  theme(axis.text=element_text(size=6),axis.title=element_text(size=8),axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

multiplot(TotalPeople,Injury,Fatalities)

Results:

Flood, hurricane, hail and tornados caused the most total damage.

  • Flood, hurricane, hail, and tornados caused the most property damage.
  • Cold, flood, hurricane, and draught caused the most crop damage.
Tornados, flood and heat caused the most injuries/death.
  • Tornados, flood and heat caused the most injuries
  • By far, head and (in a distant second) tornados caused the most fatalities.

Since tornados were in the top 3 of both damage and people related injury, analysis shows is that tornados are the most impactful event, based on this data set, taking both property damage and personal injury into account.
